Before the Underkingdom, also known as "the Spires", fell to the duergar and then to the giants, the once powerful Dwarven Kingdom was known as Dornat Murr.

Among many famous weapons and armors, the dwarven guards wielded doule-sided warhammers. One side flat and able to smash their foe, but a pick on the other side to pierce through even the most sturdy of armors. Feared were those hammers who could wreak doom onto the dwarven foes.

Lucky souls can still rarely find one of those masterpieces of dwarven craftsmenship, scattered all over the isles.

An unapologetically oversized tome of distinctly modern make boasts vivid illustrations, almost comprehensible diagrams and colourfully illuminated Loross. Perhaps unsurprisingly for a public library, it is accompanied by nearby dictionary "Loross - Contemporary Common Language, 1287". Unfortunately, the book is glaringly incomplete - paragraphs, words are oft absent. Sometimes, whole pages of the formidable tome are empty of the written word, and only supernaturally patient reader might notice that it is, in fact, updated by an occult hand, albeit at truly glacial pace.

As a second edition of the seminal work by certain Benjamin Waffleforce, notorious in equal measure of his proficiency in Variation and extravagant moustache, "Advanced Critique of Proctiv's Extraspatial Theory" is first and foremost a historical document, preserving, in no small part thanks to loquacious style of the author and expansive annotations, language, atmosphere and culture. From then-casual references, needlessly obscure allusions, indubitably included to demonstrate his remarkable erudition, occasional tirades in address of various supporters of the "Proctiv's Orthodoxy", curmudgeonous declamations on social mores, response to "slanderous insinuations regarding alleged Halfling descent", and even discussion of relative merits of smoked cheese from various enclaves, entirely unrelated to the rest of the work (continued and concluded in the Appendixes), historians worth their salt would be able to assemble a multifaceted image of life during late Golden Age of Netheril.

But no less remarkable are both "the Theory" and "the Critique", demonstrating in their depth talents of both arcanists. Even in this fragmented state, overwhelmingly obsolete many centuries ago, contents of the tome can still serve as an inspiration for a modern magician. And for those willing to dedicate enough time and energy to perform true anabasis into multi-layered metaphors, to tolerate poor humour, to endure purple prose, to storm the abundant cyphers and ultimately make peace with unavailable references, genuine High Arcana awaits.
Advanced Critique of Proctiv's Extraspatial Theory, 2nd edition (Expanded and Annotated) by B.W.

1 - Belenoth holds a neutral policy towards all races, creatures, beings, automatons as long as they will abide by the laws of the settlement. This includes, but isn't limited to: tieflings and dragon kins of any descent, aasimar, drow, sentient undead, sentient constructs and fey.

2 - The Council is the primary body of government and holds primacy in all matters; any attack to the rule of the Council, be it direct or indirect, shall not be tolerated in any way and will be strictly punished.

3 - Individuals may appeal to the Council itself to request special permits, removal of bans and in any instance where the laws of the settlement have been infringed or misapplied. The Council's last saying is definitive.

4 - Any hostile action performed within the boundaries of Belenoth or annexed territories, be it direct or indirect and damaging in any way the settlement, public and private properties, citizens, visitors or guests, will be considered as a threat to the Belenoth's integrity and punished accordingly. This includes but is not limited to: murder, harassment, assault, treasonous acts, instigation to riot, espionage, resisting arrest, theft, trading of stolen goods, possession of stolen or illegal items, bribery, extortion, blackmailing, and offensive spell-casting.

5 - Taunting and provocative, derogatory or slanderous statements are not allowed against any race, faith or ethnic group. Tolerate others as long as they abide by the laws of the settlement; harassing citizens, guests and visitors in such ways counts as a direct attack to Belenoth's peace and will be persecuted as a crime.

6 - Weapons must be sheathed and bowstrings unhooked within the settlement's limits. Self defense and defense of the settlement are the only instances where wielding a weapon will be tolerated. Refusal or resistance will result in a ban, detention or permanent confiscation of said weapons on a case-by-case basis.

7 - Slavery receives a full ban within the territory of the settlement and nearby claimed lands. Slaves smuggled into the territory are considered guests of the settlement and shall be immediately freed.

8 - Shifting is not permitted within the boundaries of Belenoth unless supervised by officials or guards or unless formally authorized by the Council itself.

9 - It's not permitted to dance the shadows within Belenoth and annexed territories unless authorized by the Council itself.
